# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xpath-query
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The **Document Object Model** (**DOM**) is a cross-platform and language-independent API that treats an HTML or XML document as a tree structure wherein each node is an object representing a part of the document.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The DOM represents a document with a logical tree.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Each branch of the tree ends in a node, and each node contains objects.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] DOM methods allow programmatic access to the tree; with them one can change the structure, style or content of a document.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Nodes can have event handlers (also known as event listeners) attached to them.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Once an event is triggered, the event handlers get executed.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The principal standardization of the DOM was handled by the World Wide Web Consortium (W3C), which last developed a recommendation in 2004.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] WHATWG took over the development of the standard, publishing it as a living document.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The W3C now publishes stable snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] JavaScript was released by Netscape Communications in 1995 within Netscape Navigator 2.0.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Netscape's competitor, Microsoft, released Internet Explorer 3.0 the following year with a reimplementation of JavaScript called JScript.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] JavaScript and JScript let web developers create web pages with client-side interactivity.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Legacy DOM was limited in the kinds of elements that could be accessed.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Form, link and image elements could be referenced with a hierarchical name that began with the root document object.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] A hierarchical name could make use of either the names or the sequential index of the traversed elements.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] For example, a form input element could be accessed as either `document.myForm.myInput` or `document.forms[0].elements[0]`.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The Legacy DOM enabled client-side form validation and simple interface interactivity like creating tooltips.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] In 1997, Netscape and Microsoft released version 4.0 of Netscape Navigator and Internet Explorer respectively, adding support for Dynamic HTML (DHTML) functionality enabling changes to a loaded HTML document.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] DHTML required extensions to the rudimentary document object that was available in the Legacy DOM implementations.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Although the Legacy DOM implementations were largely compatible since JScript was based on JavaScript, the DHTML DOM extensions were developed in parallel by each browser maker and remained incompatible.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] These versions of the DOM became known as the "Intermediate DOM".
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] After the standardization of ECMAScript, the W3C DOM Working Group began drafting a standard DOM specification.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The completed specification, known as "DOM Level 1", became a W3C Recommendation in late 1998.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] By 2005, large parts of W3C DOM were well-supported by common ECMAScript-enabled browsers, including Internet Explorer 6 (from 2001), Opera, Safari and Gecko-based browsers (like Mozilla, Firefox, SeaMonkey and Camino).
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The W3C DOM Working Group published its final recommendation and subsequently disbanded in 2004.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Development efforts migrated to the WHATWG, which continues to maintain a living standard.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] In 2009, the Web Applications group reorganized DOM activities at the W3C.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] In 2013, due to a lack of progress and the impending release of HTML5, the DOM Level 4 specification was reassigned to the HTML Working Group to expedite its completion.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Meanwhile, in 2015, the Web Applications group was disbanded and DOM stewardship passed to the Web Platform group.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Beginning with the publication of DOM Level 4 in 2015, the W3C creates new recommendations based on snapshots of the WHATWG standard.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] To render a document such as a HTML page, most web browsers use an internal model similar to the DOM.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The nodes of every document are organized in a tree structure, called the *DOM tree*, with the topmost node named as "Document object".
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] When an HTML page is rendered in browsers, the browser downloads the HTML into local memory and automatically parses it to display the page on screen.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] However, the DOM does not necessarily need to be represented as a tree, and some browsers have used other internal models.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] When a web page is loaded, the browser creates a Document Object Model of the page, which is an object oriented representation of an HTML document that acts as an interface between JavaScript and the document itself.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] A Document Object Model (DOM) tree is a hierarchical representation of an HTML or XML document.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] It consists of a root node, which is the document itself, and a series of child nodes that represent the elements, attributes, and text content of the document.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Each node in the tree has a parent node, except for the root node, and can have multiple child nodes.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Elements in an HTML or XML document are represented as nodes in the DOM tree.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Each element node has a tag name and attributes, and can contain other element nodes or text nodes as children.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Text content within an element is represented as a text node in the DOM tree.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Text nodes do not have attributes or child nodes and are therefore always leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] For example, the text content "My Website" in the title element and "Welcome" in the h1 element are both represented as text nodes.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Attributes of an element are represented as properties of the element node in the DOM tree.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The DOM tree can be manipulated using JavaScript or other programming languages.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Common tasks include navigating the tree, adding, removing, and modifying nodes, and getting and setting the properties of nodes.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The DOM API provides a set of methods and properties to perform these operations, such as `getElementById`, `createElement`, `appendChild`, and `innerHTML`.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Another way to create a DOM structure is using the innerHTML property to insert HTML code as a string, creating the elements and children in the process.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Another method is to use a JavaScript library or framework such as jQuery, AngularJS, React, Vue.js, Svelte, etc.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] These libraries provide an efficient way to create, manipulate and interact with the DOM.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] It is also possible to create a DOM structure from an XML or JSON data, using JavaScript methods to parse the data and create the nodes accordingly.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Creating a DOM structure does not necessarily mean that it will be displayed in the web page, it only exists in memory and should be appended to the document body or a specific container to be rendered.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] In summary, creating a DOM structure involves creating individual nodes and organizing them in a hierarchical structure using JavaScript or other programming languages, and it can be done using several methods depending on the use case and the developer's preference.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Because the DOM supports navigation in any direction (e.g., parent and previous sibling) and allows for arbitrary modifications, implementations typically buffer the document.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] However, a DOM need not originate in a serialized document at all, but can be created in place with the DOM API.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] And even before the idea of the DOM originated, there were implementations of equivalent structure with persistent disk representation and rapid access, for example DynaText's model disclosed in and various database approaches.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Web browsers rely on layout engines to parse HTML into a DOM.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Some layout engines, such as Trident/MSHTML, are associated primarily or exclusively with a particular browser, such as Internet Explorer.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] Others, including Blink, WebKit, and Gecko, are shared by a number of browsers, such as Google Chrome, Opera, Safari, and Firefox.
[src:xpath-query/document-object-model] The different layout engines implement the DOM standards to varying degrees of compliance.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In computing, a **namespace** is a set of signs (*names*) that are used to identify and refer to objects of various kinds.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A namespace ensures that all of a given set of objects have unique names so that they can be easily identified.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Namespaces are commonly structured as hierarchies to allow reuse of names in different contexts.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] As an analogy, consider a system of naming of people where each person has a given name, as well as a family name shared with their relatives.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] If the first names of family members are unique only within each family, then each person can be uniquely identified by the combination of first name and family name; there is only one Jane Doe, though there may be many Janes.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Within the namespace of the Doe family, just "Jane" suffices to unambiguously designate this person, while within the "global" namespace of all people, the full name must be used.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Prominent examples for namespaces include file systems, which assign names to files.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Some programming languages organize their variables and subroutines in namespaces.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Computer networks and distributed systems assign names to resources, such as computers, printers, websites, and remote files.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Operating systems can partition kernel resources by isolated namespaces to support OS-level virtualization containers.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Similarly, hierarchical file systems organize files in directories.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Each directory is a separate namespace, so that the directories "letters" and "invoices" may both contain a file "to_jane".
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In computer programming, namespaces are typically used to group symbols and identifiers around a given task and to avoid name collisions between multiple identifiers that share the same name.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In computer networking, the Domain Name System organizes websites (and other resources) into hierarchical namespaces.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Element names are defined by the developer.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] This often results in a conflict when trying to mix XML documents from different XML applications.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] If these XML fragments were added together, there would be a name conflict.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Both contain a `<table>...</table>` element, but the elements have different content and meaning.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] An XML parser will not know how to handle these differences.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Name conflicts in XML can easily be avoided using a name prefix.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] The following XML distinguishes between information about the HTML table and furniture by prefixing "h" and "f" at the beginning of the elements.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A name in a namespace consists of a namespace name and a local name.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] The namespace name is usually applied as a prefix to the local name.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] When local names are used by themselves, name resolution is used to decide which (if any) particular name is alluded to by some particular local name.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Delegation of responsibilities between parties is important in real-world applications, such as the structure of the World Wide Web.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Namespaces allow delegation of identifier assignment to multiple name issuing organisations whilst retaining global uniqueness.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A central Registration authority registers the assigned namespace names allocated.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Each namespace name is allocated to an organisation which is subsequently responsible for the assignment of names in their allocated namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] This organisation may be a name issuing organisation that assign the names themselves, or another Registration authority which further delegates parts of their namespace to different organisations.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A naming scheme that allows subdelegation of namespaces to third parties is a **hierarchical namespace**.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A hierarchy is recursive if the syntax for the namespace names is the same for each subdelegation.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] An example of a recursive hierarchy is the Domain name system.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] An example of a non-recursive hierarchy are Uniform Resource Name representing an Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) number.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A namespace name may provide context (scope in computer science) to a name, and the terms are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] However, the context of a name may also be provided by other factors, such as the location where it occurs or the syntax of the name.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For many programming languages, namespace is a context for their identifiers.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In an operating system, an example of namespace is a directory.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Each name in a directory uniquely identifies one file or subdirectory.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] As a rule, names in a namespace cannot have more than one meaning; that is, different meanings cannot share the same name in the same namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A namespace is also called a context, because the same name in different namespaces can have different meanings, each one appropriate for its namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] As well as its abstract language technical usage as described above, some languages have a specific keyword used for explicit namespace control, amongst other uses.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A namespace in computer science (sometimes also called a **name scope**) is an abstract container or environment created to hold a logical grouping of unique identifiers or symbols (i.e. names).
[src:xpath-query/namespace] An identifier defined in a namespace is associated only with that namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] The same identifier can be independently defined in multiple namespaces.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] That is, an identifier defined in one namespace may or may not have the same meaning as the same identifier defined in another namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Languages that support namespaces specify the rules that determine to which namespace an identifier (not its definition) belongs.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] This concept can be illustrated with an analogy.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Imagine that two companies, X and Y, each assign ID numbers to their employees.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] X should not have two employees with the same ID number, and likewise for Y; but it is not a problem for the same ID number to be used at both companies.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For example, if Bill works for company X and Jane works for company Y, then it is not a problem for each of them to be employee #123.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In this analogy, the ID number is the identifier, and the company serves as the namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] It does not cause problems for the same identifier to identify a different person in each namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In large computer programs or documents it is common to have hundreds or thousands of identifiers.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Namespaces (or a similar technique, see Emulating namespaces) provide a mechanism for hiding local identifiers.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] They provide a means of grouping logically related identifiers into corresponding namespaces, thereby making the system more modular.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Data storage devices and many modern programming languages support namespaces.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Storage devices use directories (or folders) as namespaces.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] This allows two files with the same name to be stored on the device so long as they are stored in different directories.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] C++, Python), the identifiers naming namespaces are themselves associated with an enclosing namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Thus, in these languages namespaces can nest, forming a namespace tree.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] At the root of this tree is the unnamed **global namespace**.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] It is possible to use anonymous structs as namespaces in C since C99.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In C++, a namespace is defined with a namespace block.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Within this block, identifiers can be used exactly as they are declared.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Outside of this block, the namespace specifier must be prefixed.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For example, outside of `namespace abc`, `bar` must be written `abc::bar` to be accessed.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] C++ includes another construct that makes this verbosity unnecessary.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] to a piece of code, the prefix `abc::` is no longer needed.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Identifiers that are not explicitly declared within a namespace are considered to be in the global namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] These identifiers can be used exactly as they are declared, or, since the global namespace is unnamed, the namespace specifier `::` can be prefixed.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For example, `foo` can also be written `::foo`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Namespace resolution in C++ is hierarchical.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] This means that within the hypothetical namespace `food::soup`, the identifier `Chicken` refers to `food::soup::Chicken`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] If `food::soup::Chicken` doesn't exist, it then refers to `food::Chicken`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] If neither `food::soup::Chicken` nor `food::Chicken` exist, `Chicken` refers to `::Chicken`, an identifier in the global namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Namespaces in C++ are most often used to avoid naming collisions.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Although namespaces are used extensively in recent C++ code, most older code does not use this facility because it did not exist in early versions of the language.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For example, the entire C++ Standard Library is defined within `namespace std`, but before standardization many components were originally in the global namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] The `using` statement can be used to import a symbol into the current scope.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] The use of the `using` statements in headers for reasons other than backwards compatibility (e.g., convenience) is considered to be against good code practices, as those `using` statements propagate into all translation units that include the header.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] However, modules do not export `using` statements unless explicitly marked `export`, making `using` statements safer to use.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For instance, one can import a module `wikipedia.project.util` with matching namespace `wikipedia::project::util` and then use `using` statements on symbols from that namespace to simplify verbose namespaces.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Unlike other languages like Java or Rust, C++ modules, namespaces and source file structure do not necessarily match, though it is convention to match them for clarity (for example, module `abc.def.uvw.XYZ` matches namespaced class `abc::def::uvw::XYZ` and resides in file `abc/def/uvw/XYZ.cppm`).
[src:xpath-query/namespace] `using` should be used to simplify verbose nested namespaces when modular translation units are used.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] C++11 introduces *inline namespaces*, which is such that its members are treated as if they are also members of the enclosing namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] It is declared by writing `inline namespace`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] It is akin to an implicit `using namespace` statement, meaning qualifying symbols in it is optional.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] If a namespace `a` contains an inline namespace `b`, which in turn contains another inline namespace `c`, then members of `c` can be accessed as if they were members of `a` or `b`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A primary use case for inline namespaces is ABI compatibility and versioning.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] By placing different versions of an API within distinct inline namespaces (e.g., `v1`, `v2`), and then making the currently desired version inline, library developers can manage ABI compatibility.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] When a new version is released, the inline keyword can be moved to the new version's namespace, allowing users to automatically link against the new version while still enabling access to older versions through explicit qualification.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Namespaces are heavily used in C# language.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] All .NET framework classes are organized in namespaces, to be used more clearly and to avoid chaos.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Also, custom namespaces are used extensively by programmers, to organize their work and to avoid naming collisions.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] This eliminates the need to mention the complete name of all classes in that namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In the above examples, `System` is a namespace, and `Console` and `Convert` are classes defined within `System`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Unlike C++, `using` can only import all symbols in a namespace (much like `using namespace` from C++, `use *` in Rust, or `import *` in Java).
[src:xpath-query/namespace] It cannot be used to import individual symbols and classes like it is used in Java.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Unlike C++, C# namespaces do not allow relative referencing of symbols.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For example, the class `Foo.Bar.Baz.Qux` cannot be referred to as `Baz.Qux` even if referred to from within namespace `Foo.Bar`: either the namespace `Foo.Bar.Baz` must be imported to refer to class `Qux`, or `Foo.Bar.Baz.Qux` must be fully qualified.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In Java, the idea of a namespace is embodied in Java packages.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] All code belongs to a package, although that package need not be explicitly named.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Code from other packages is accessed by prefixing the package name before the appropriate identifier, for example `class String` in `package java.lang` can be referred to as `java.lang.String` (this is known as the fully qualified class name).
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Like C++, Java offers a construct that makes it unnecessary to type the package name (`import`).
[src:xpath-query/namespace] However, certain features (such as reflection) require the programmer to use the fully qualified name.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Unlike C++, namespaces in Java are not hierarchical as to the syntax of the language.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] However, packages are named in a hierarchical manner.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For example, all packages beginning with `java` are a part of the Java platform—the package `java.lang` contains classes core to the language, and `java.lang.reflect` contains core classes specifically relating to reflection.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In Java (and Ada, C#, and others), namespaces/packages express semantic categories of code.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For example, in C#, `namespace System` contains code provided by the system (the .NET framework).
[src:xpath-query/namespace] How specific these categories are and how deep the hierarchies go differ from language to language.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Function and class scopes can be viewed as implicit namespaces that are inextricably linked with visibility, accessibility, and object lifetime.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In Java, packages cannot be partially qualified like they can in C++.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For instance, it is not possible to import the `java` namespace and then refer to `java.util.ArrayList` as `util.ArrayList`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Symbols must either be fully qualified or imported completely into scope.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] `import` statements are not transitive nor can they be deliberately marked `export` like in C++.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] All `import` statements must appear at the beginning of the file, and cannot be written at any other scope.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] This is in contrast to C++, where the `std` namespace can be imported by writing `using namespace std;`, and then `std::chrono::system_clock` can be referred to as `chrono::system_clock`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Because Java does not support independent functions outside of classes, static class methods and so-called "utility classes" (classes with private constructors and all methods and fields static) are the equivalent to C++-style namespaces.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Some examples are `java.lang.Math`, which contains the constants like `Math.PI` and methods like `Math.sin()`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] `import` statements can be used to import all symbols in a package, called a glob import, which is similar to `using namespace` in C++.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For instance, writing `import java.util.*;` imports all classes in the `java.util` package.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] This however, can cause symbol pollution within a file.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Furthermore, using glob import statements on packages that have classes with the same name can cause ambiguity, and will fail to compile.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] However, `java.lang.*` is implicitly imported into all Java source files by default.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Kotlin packages are very similar to Java packages, but unlike Java where only class-like objects may reside directly in a package, any top-level symbol (such as a variable, class, type alias, etc.) may live directly inside a package.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Namespaces were introduced into PHP from version 5.3 onwards.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Naming collision of classes, functions and variables can be avoided.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In PHP, a namespace is defined with a namespace block.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In Python, namespaces are defined by the individual modules, and since modules can be contained in hierarchical packages, then namespaces are hierarchical too.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In general when a module is imported then the names defined in the module are defined via that module's namespace, and are accessed in from the calling modules by using the fully qualified name.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Since this directly imports names (without qualification) it can overwrite existing names with no warnings.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A special form of the statement is `from ... import *` which imports all names defined in the named package directly in the calling module's namespace.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In Rust, a namespace is called a "module" and declared using `mod`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Symbols inside the module are by default private, and cannot be accessed externally, unless declared with the `pub` keyword which exposes them.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Modules can have sub-modules inside of them, allowing for nested namespaces.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Similar to the `using` keyword in C++, Rust has the `use` keyword to import symbols into the current scope.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Writing `mod util;` indicates to the compiler to find either a file named `util.rs` or `util/mod.rs`.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] `crate` in a `use` statement refers to the root of the current "crate" (project), while `super` can be used to refer to the parent module.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] The `use` keyword in Rust is more versatile than its counterpart `using` in C++.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In addition to importing single symbols, symbol aliasing with `as` and glob imports, `use` can import multiple symbols on the same line using braces (which may be nested), import individual namespaces, and do all of the above in a single statement.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In XML, the XML namespace specification enables the names of elements and attributes in an XML document to be unique, similar to the role of namespaces in programming languages.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Using XML namespaces, XML documents may contain element or attribute names from more than one XML vocabulary.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In SAP systems (especially ABAP environments), namespaces are used to prevent naming collisions between standard SAP-delivered objects and customer or partner developments.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] A namespace identifier is delimited with “/” (for example `/MYNS/`) and is reserved via SAP’s namespace registration process.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Once reserved, objects created under that namespace are uniquely identifiable and protected from unintended overwrite by SAP upgrades or imports.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In modern SAP landscapes (such as ABAP in the cloud and HDI containers), namespaces are also used to semantically group development artifacts or bundles.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] In programming languages lacking language support for namespaces, namespaces can be emulated to some extent by using an identifier naming convention.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] For example, C libraries such as libpng often use a fixed prefix for all functions and variables that are part of their exposed interface.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] This naming convention provides reasonable assurance that the identifiers are unique and can therefore be used in larger programs without naming collisions.
[src:xpath-query/namespace] Likewise, many packages originally written in Fortran (e.g., BLAS, LAPACK) reserve the first few letters of a function's name to indicate the group to which the function belongs.
[src:xpath-query/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:xpath-query/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:xpath-query/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:xpath-query/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:xpath-query/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The design goals of XML emphasize simplicity, generality, and usability across the Internet.
[src:xpath-query/xml] It is a textual data format with strong support via Unicode for different human languages.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Although the design of XML focuses on documents, the language is widely used for the representation of arbitrary data structures, such as those used in web services.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Several schema systems exist to aid in the definition of XML-based languages, while programmers have developed many application programming interfaces (APIs) to aid the processing of XML data.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The main purpose of XML is serialization, i.e. storing, transmitting, and reconstructing arbitrary data.
[src:xpath-query/xml] For two disparate systems to exchange information, they need to agree upon a file format.
[src:xpath-query/xml] It is therefore analogous to a lingua franca for representing information.
[src:xpath-query/xml] As a markup language, XML labels, categorizes, and structurally organizes information.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML tags represent the data structure and contain metadata.
[src:xpath-query/xml] What is within the tags is data, encoded in the way the XML standard specifies.
[src:xpath-query/xml] An additional XML schema (XSD) defines the necessary metadata for interpreting and validating XML.
[src:xpath-query/xml] (This is also referred to as the canonical schema.) An XML document that adheres to basic XML rules is "well-formed"; one that adheres to its schema is "valid".
[src:xpath-query/xml] IETF RFC 7303 (which supersedes the older RFC 3023), provides rules for the construction of media types for use in XML message.
[src:xpath-query/xml] It defines three media types: `application/xml` (`text/xml` is an alias), `application/xml-external-parsed-entity` (`text/xml-external-parsed-entity` is an alias) and `application/xml-dtd`.
[src:xpath-query/xml] They are used for transmitting raw XML files without exposing their internal semantics.
[src:xpath-query/xml] RFC 7303 further recommends that XML-based languages be given media types ending in `+xml`, for example, `image/svg+xml` for SVG.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Further guidelines for the use of XML in a networked context appear in RFC 3470, also known as IETF BCP 70, a document covering many aspects of designing and deploying an XML-based language.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML has come into common use for the interchange of data over the Internet.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Hundreds of document formats using XML syntax have been developed, including RSS, Atom, Office Open XML, OpenDocument, SVG, COLLADA, and XHTML.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML also provides the base language for communication protocols such as SOAP and XMPP.
[src:xpath-query/xml] It is one of the message exchange formats used in the Asynchronous JavaScript and XML (AJAX) programming technique.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Many industry data standards, such as Health Level 7, OpenTravel Alliance, FpML, MISMO, and the National Information Exchange Model are based on XML and the rich features of the XML schema specification.
[src:xpath-query/xml] In publishing, Darwin Information Typing Architecture is an XML industry data standard.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML is used extensively to underpin various publishing formats.
[src:xpath-query/xml] One of the applications of XML in science is the representation of operational meteorology information based on IWXXM standards.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The material in this section is based on the XML Specification.
[src:xpath-query/xml] This is not an exhaustive list of all the constructs that appear in XML; it provides an introduction to the key constructs most often encountered in day-to-day use.
[src:xpath-query/xml] character (except Null) may appear in an (1.1) XML document (while some are discouraged).
[src:xpath-query/xml] The specification places requirements on what an XML processor must do and not do, but the application is outside its scope.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Strings of characters that are not markup are content.
[src:xpath-query/xml] are classified as markup, while the text between them is classified as content.
[src:xpath-query/xml] In addition, whitespace before and after the outermost element is classified as markup.
[src:xpath-query/xml] is a logical document component that either begins with a start-tag and ends with a matching end-tag or consists only of an empty-element tag.
[src:xpath-query/xml] that exists within a start-tag or empty-element tag.
[src:xpath-query/xml] , where the names of the attributes are "src" and "alt", and their values are "madonna.jpg" and "Madonna" respectively.
[src:xpath-query/xml] , where the name of the attribute is "number" and its value is "3".
[src:xpath-query/xml] An XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:xpath-query/xml] with some format beyond what XML defines itself.
[src:xpath-query/xml] that describes some information about themselves.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML documents consist entirely of characters from the Unicode repertoire.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Except for a small number of specifically excluded control characters, any character defined by Unicode may appear within the content of an XML document.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML includes facilities for identifying the *encoding* of the Unicode characters that make up the document, and for expressing characters that, for one reason or another, cannot be used directly.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML 1.1 extends the set of allowed characters to include all the above, plus the remaining characters in the range U+0001–U+001F.
[src:xpath-query/xml] At the same time, however, it restricts the use of C0 and C1 control characters other than U+0009 (Horizontal Tab), U+000A (Line Feed), U+000D (Carriage Return), and U+0085 (Next Line) by requiring them to be written in escaped form (for example U+0001 must be written as `&#x01;` or its equivalent).
[src:xpath-query/xml] In the case of C1 characters, this restriction is a backwards incompatibility; it was introduced to allow common encoding errors to be detected.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The code point U+0000 (Null) is the only character that is not permitted in any XML 1.1 document.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The Unicode character set can be encoded into bytes for storage or transmission in a variety of different ways, called "encodings".
[src:xpath-query/xml] Unicode itself defines encodings that cover the entire repertoire; well-known ones include UTF-8 (which the XML standard recommends using, without a BOM) and UTF-16.
[src:xpath-query/xml] There are many other text encodings that predate Unicode, such as ASCII and various ISO/IEC 8859; their character repertoires are in every case subsets of the Unicode character set.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML allows the use of any of the Unicode-defined encodings and any other encodings whose characters also appear in Unicode.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML also provides a mechanism whereby an XML processor can reliably, without any prior knowledge, determine which encoding is being used.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Encodings other than UTF-8 and UTF-16 are not necessarily recognized by every XML parser (and in some cases not even UTF-16, even though the standard mandates it to also be recognized).
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML provides *escape* facilities for including characters that are problematic to include directly.
[src:xpath-query/xml] All permitted Unicode characters may be represented with a *numeric character reference*.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Consider the Chinese character "中", whose numeric code in Unicode is hexadecimal 4E2D, or decimal 20,013.
[src:xpath-query/xml] A user whose keyboard offers no method for entering this character could still insert it in an XML document encoded either as `&#20013;` or `&#x4e2d;`.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Similarly, the string "I <3 Jörg" could be encoded for inclusion in an XML document as `I &lt;3 J&#xF6;rg`.
[src:xpath-query/xml] `&#0;` is not permitted because the null character is one of the control characters excluded from XML, even when using a numeric character reference.
[src:xpath-query/xml] An alternative encoding mechanism such as Base64 is needed to represent such characters.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Comments may appear anywhere in a document outside other markup.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Comments cannot appear before the XML declaration.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Comments begin with `<!--` and end with `-->`.
[src:xpath-query/xml] For compatibility with SGML, the string "--" (double-hyphen) is not allowed inside comments; this means comments cannot be nested.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The ampersand has no special significance within comments, so entity and character references are not recognized as such, and there is no way to represent characters outside the character set of the document encoding.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML 1.0 (Fifth Edition) and XML 1.1 support the direct use of almost any Unicode character in element names, attributes, comments, character data, and processing instructions (other than the ones that have special symbolic meaning in XML itself, such as the less-than sign, "<").
[src:xpath-query/xml] The XML specification defines an XML document as a well-formed text, meaning that it satisfies a list of syntax rules provided in the specification.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The definition of an XML document excludes texts that contain violations of well-formedness rules; they are simply not XML.
[src:xpath-query/xml] An XML processor that encounters such a violation is required to report such errors and to cease normal processing.
[src:xpath-query/xml] This policy, occasionally referred to as "draconian error handling", stands in notable contrast to the behavior of programs that process HTML, which are designed to produce a reasonable result even in the presence of severe markup errors.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML's policy in this area has been criticized as a violation of Postel's law ("Be conservative in what you send; be liberal in what you accept").
[src:xpath-query/xml] The XML specification defines a valid XML document as a well-formed XML document which also conforms to the rules of a Document Type Definition (DTD).
[src:xpath-query/xml] In addition to being well formed, an XML document may be *valid*.
[src:xpath-query/xml] This means that it contains a reference to a Document Type Definition (DTD), and that its elements and attributes are declared in that DTD and follow the grammatical rules for them that the DTD specifies.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML processors are classified as *validating* or *non-validating* depending on whether or not they check XML documents for validity.
[src:xpath-query/xml] A processor that discovers a validity error must be able to report it, but may continue normal processing.
[src:xpath-query/xml] A DTD is an example of a *schema* or *grammar*.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Since the initial publication of XML 1.0, there has been substantial work in the area of schema languages for XML.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Such schema languages typically constrain the set of elements that may be used in a document, which attributes may be applied to them, the order in which they may appear, and the allowable parent/child relationships.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The oldest schema language for XML is the document type definition (DTD), inherited from SGML.
[src:xpath-query/xml] DTD technology is still used in many applications because of its ubiquity.
[src:xpath-query/xml] A newer schema language, described by the W3C as the successor of DTDs, is XML Schema, often referred to by the initialism for XML Schema instances, XSD (XML Schema Definition).
[src:xpath-query/xml] XSDs are far more powerful than DTDs in describing XML languages.
[src:xpath-query/xml] They use a rich datatyping system and allow for more detailed constraints on an XML document's logical structure.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XSDs also use an XML-based format, which makes it possible to use ordinary XML tools to help process them.
[src:xpath-query/xml] RELAX NG (Regular Language for XML Next Generation) was initially specified by OASIS and is now a standard (Part 2: *Regular-grammar-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:xpath-query/xml] RELAX NG schemas may be written in either an XML based syntax or a more compact non-XML syntax; the two syntaxes are isomorphic and James Clark's conversion tool—Trang—can convert between them without loss of information.
[src:xpath-query/xml] RELAX NG has a simpler definition and validation framework than XML Schema, making it easier to use and implement.
[src:xpath-query/xml] It also has the ability to use datatype framework plug-ins; a RELAX NG schema author, for example, can require values in an XML document to conform to definitions in XML Schema Datatypes.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Schematron is a language for making assertions about the presence or absence of patterns in an XML document.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Schematron is now a standard (Part 3: *Rule-based validation* of ISO/IEC 19757 – DSDL).
[src:xpath-query/xml] DSDL (Document Schema Definition Languages) is a multi-part ISO/IEC standard (ISO/IEC 19757) that brings together a comprehensive set of small schema languages, each targeted at specific problems.
[src:xpath-query/xml] DSDL includes RELAX NG full and compact syntax, Schematron assertion language, and languages for defining datatypes, character repertoire constraints, renaming and entity expansion, and namespace-based routing of document fragments to different validators.
[src:xpath-query/xml] DSDL schema languages do not have the vendor support of XML Schemas yet, and are to some extent a grassroots reaction of industrial publishers to the lack of utility of XML Schemas for publishing.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Some schema languages not only describe the structure of a particular XML format but also offer limited facilities to influence processing of individual XML files that conform to this format.
[src:xpath-query/xml] DTDs and XSDs both have this ability; they can for instance provide the infoset augmentation facility and attribute defaults.
[src:xpath-query/xml] RELAX NG and Schematron intentionally do not provide these.
[src:xpath-query/xml] A cluster of specifications closely related to XML have been developed, starting soon after the initial publication of XML 1.0.
[src:xpath-query/xml] It is frequently the case that the term "XML" is used to refer to XML together with one or more of these other technologies that have come to be seen as part of the XML core.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Some other specifications conceived as part of the "XML Core" have failed to find wide adoption, including XInclude, XLink, and XPointer.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The design goals of XML include, "It shall be easy to write programs which process XML documents." Despite this, the XML specification contains almost no information about how programmers might go about doing such processing.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The XML Infoset specification provides a vocabulary to refer to the constructs within an XML document, but does not provide any guidance on how to access this information.
[src:xpath-query/xml] A variety of APIs for accessing XML have been developed and used, and some have been standardized.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Stream-oriented facilities require less memory and, for certain tasks based on a linear traversal of an XML document, are faster and simpler than other alternatives.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Tree-traversal and data-binding APIs typically require the use of much more memory, but are often found more convenient for use by programmers; some include declarative retrieval of document components via the use of XPath expressions.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XSLT is designed for declarative description of XML document transformations, and has been widely implemented both in server-side packages and Web browsers.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XQuery overlaps XSLT in its functionality, but is designed more for searching of large XML databases.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Simple API for XML (SAX) is a lexical, event-driven API in which a document is read serially and its contents are reported as callbacks to various methods on a handler object of the user's design.
[src:xpath-query/xml] SAX is fast and efficient to implement, but difficult to use for extracting information at random from the XML, since it tends to burden the application author with keeping track of what part of the document is being processed.
[src:xpath-query/xml] It is better suited to situations in which certain types of information are always handled the same way, no matter where they occur in the document.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Pull parsing treats the document as a series of items read in sequence using the iterator design pattern.
[src:xpath-query/xml] A pull parser creates an iterator that sequentially visits the various elements, attributes, and data in an XML document.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Code that uses this iterator can test the current item (to tell, for example, whether it is a start-tag or end-tag, or text), and inspect its attributes (local name, namespace, values of XML attributes, value of text, etc.), and can also move the iterator to the next item.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The code can thus extract information from the document as it traverses it.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The recursive-descent approach tends to lend itself to keeping data as typed local variables in the code doing the parsing, while SAX, for instance, typically requires a parser to manually maintain intermediate data within a stack of elements that are parent elements of the element being parsed.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Pull-parsing code can be more straightforward to understand and maintain than SAX parsing code.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The Document Object Model (DOM) is an interface that allows for navigation of the entire document as if it were a tree of node objects representing the document's contents.
[src:xpath-query/xml] A DOM document can be created by a parser, or can be generated manually by users (with limitations).
[src:xpath-query/xml] Data types in DOM nodes are abstract; implementations provide their own programming language-specific bindings.
[src:xpath-query/xml] DOM implementations tend to be memory intensive, as they generally require the entire document to be loaded into memory and constructed as a tree of objects before access is allowed.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML data binding is a technique for simplifying development of applications that need to work with XML documents.
[src:xpath-query/xml] It involves mapping the XML document to a hierarchy of strongly typed objects, rather than using the generic objects created by a DOM parser.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The resulting code is often easier to read and maintain, and it can help to identify problems at compile time rather than run-time.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML data binding is particularly well-suited for applications where the document structure is known and fixed at the time the application is written.
[src:xpath-query/xml] By creating a strongly typed representation of the XML data, developers can take advantage of modern integrated development environments (IDEs) that provide features like auto-complete, code refactoring, and code highlighting.
[src:xpath-query/xml] This can make it easier to write correct and efficient code, and reduce the risk of errors and bugs.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Example data-binding systems include the Java Architecture for XML Binding (JAXB), XML Serialization in .NET Framework, and XML serialization in gSOAP.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML has appeared as a first-class data type in other languages.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The ECMAScript for XML (E4X) extension to the ECMAScript/JavaScript language explicitly defines two specific objects (XML and XMLList) for JavaScript, which support XML document nodes and XML node lists as distinct objects and use a dot-notation specifying parent-child relationships.
[src:xpath-query/xml] E4X is supported by the Mozilla 2.5+ browsers (though now deprecated) and Adobe Actionscript but has not been widely adopted.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Similar notations are used in Microsoft's LINQ implementation for Microsoft .NET 3.5 and above, and in Scala (which uses the Java VM).
[src:xpath-query/xml] The open-source xmlsh application, which provides a Linux-like shell with special features for XML manipulation, similarly treats XML as a data type, using the <[ ]> notation.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The Resource Description Framework defines a data type `rdf:XMLLiteral` to hold wrapped, canonical XML.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Facebook has produced extensions to the PHP and JavaScript languages that add XML to the core syntax in a similar fashion to E4X, namely XHP and JSX respectively.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML is an application profile of SGML (ISO 8879).
[src:xpath-query/xml] The versatility of SGML for dynamic information display was understood by early digital media publishers in the late 1980s prior to the rise of the Internet.
[src:xpath-query/xml] By the mid-1990s some practitioners of SGML had gained experience with the then-new World Wide Web, and believed that SGML offered solutions to some of the problems the Web was likely to face as it grew.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Dan Connolly added SGML to the list of W3C's activities when he joined the staff in 1995; work began in mid-1996 when Sun Microsystems engineer Jon Bosak developed a charter and recruited collaborators.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Bosak was well-connected in the small community of people who had experience both in SGML and the Web.
[src:xpath-query/xml] XML was compiled by a working group of eleven members, supported by a (roughly) 150-member Interest Group.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Technical debate took place on the Interest Group mailing list and issues were resolved by consensus or, when that failed, majority vote of the Working Group.
[src:xpath-query/xml] A record of design decisions and their rationales was compiled by Michael Sperberg-McQueen on December 4, 1997.
[src:xpath-query/xml] James Clark served as Technical Lead of the Working Group, notably contributing the empty-element `<empty />` syntax and the name "XML".
[src:xpath-query/xml] Other names that had been put forward for consideration included "MAGMA" (Minimal Architecture for Generalized Markup Applications), "SLIM" (Structured Language for Internet Markup) and "MGML" (Minimal Generalized Markup Language).
[src:xpath-query/xml] The co-editors of the specification were originally Tim Bray and Michael Sperberg-McQueen.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Halfway through the project, Bray accepted a consulting engagement with Netscape, provoking vociferous protests from Microsoft.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Bray was temporarily asked to resign the editorship.
[src:xpath-query/xml] This led to intense dispute in the Working Group, eventually solved by the appointment of Microsoft's Jean Paoli as a third co-editor.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The XML Working Group communicated primarily through email and weekly teleconferences.
[src:xpath-query/xml] The major design decisions were reached in a short burst of intense work between August and November 1996, when the first Working Draft of an XML specification was published.
[src:xpath-query/xml] Further design work continued through 1997, and XML 1.0 became a W3C Recommendation on February 10, 1998.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The XPath language is based on a tree representation of the XML document, and provides the ability to navigate around the tree, selecting nodes by a variety of criteria.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] In popular use (though not in the official specification), an XPath expression is often referred to simply as "an XPath".
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Originally motivated by a desire to provide a common syntax and behavior model between XPointer and XSLT, subsets of the XPath query language are used in other W3C specifications such as XML Schema, XForms and the Internationalization Tag Set (ITS).
[src:xpath-query/xpath] XPath has been adopted by a number of XML processing libraries and tools, many of which also offer CSS Selectors, another W3C standard, as a simpler alternative to XPath.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] There are several versions of XPath in use.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] However, XPath 1.0 is still the version that is most widely available.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The most important kind of expression in XPath is a *location path*.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] A location path consists of a sequence of *location steps*.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] An XPath expression is evaluated with respect to a *context node*.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] An Axis Specifier such as 'child' or 'descendant' specifies the direction to navigate from the context node.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The node test and the predicate are used to filter the nodes specified by the axis specifier: For example, the node test 'A' requires that all nodes navigated to must have label 'A'.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] A predicate can be used to specify that the selected nodes have certain properties, which are specified by XPath expressions themselves.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The XPath syntax comes in two flavors: the *abbreviated syntax*, is more compact and allows XPaths to be written and read easily using intuitive and, in many cases, familiar characters and constructs.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The *full syntax* is more verbose, but allows for more options to be specified, and is more descriptive if read carefully.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The compact notation allows many defaults and abbreviations for common cases.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] that selects C elements that are children of B elements that are children of the A element that forms the outermost element of the XML document.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The XPath syntax is designed to mimic URI (Uniform Resource Identifier) and Unix-style file path syntax.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] More complex expressions can be constructed by specifying an axis other than the default 'child' axis, a node test other than a simple name, or predicates, which can be written in square brackets after any step.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] selects the first child ('`*[1]`'), whatever its name, of every B element that itself is a child or other, deeper descendant ('`//`') of an A element that is a child of the current context node (the expression does not begin with a '`/`').
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The predicate `[1]` binds more tightly than the `/` operator.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] To select the first node selected by the expression `A//B/*`, write `(A//B/*)[1]`.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Note also, index values in XPath predicates (technically, 'proximity positions' of XPath node sets) start from 1, not 0 as common in languages like C and Java.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Here, in each step of the XPath, the **axis** (e.g.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] `child` or `descendant-or-self`) is explicitly specified, followed by `::` and then the **node test**, such as `A` or `node()` in the examples above.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Axis specifiers indicate navigation direction within the tree representation of the XML document.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] As an example of using the **attribute** axis in abbreviated syntax, `//a/@href` selects the attribute called `href` in `a` elements anywhere in the document tree.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The expression **.** (an abbreviation for **self::node()**) is most commonly used within a predicate to refer to the currently selected node.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] For example, `h3[.='See also']` selects an element called `h3` in the current context, whose text content is `See also`.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Node tests may consist of specific node names or more general expressions.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] In the case of an XML document in which the namespace prefix `gs` has been defined, `//gs:enquiry` will find all the `enquiry` elements in that namespace, and `//gs:*` will find all elements, regardless of local name, in that namespace.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Predicates, written as expressions in square brackets, can be used to filter a node-set according to some condition.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] For example, `a` returns a node-set (all the `a` elements which are children of the context node), and `a[@href='help.php']` keeps only those elements having an `href` attribute with the value `help.php`.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] There is no limit to the number of predicates in a step, and they need not be confined to the last step in an XPath.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Paths specified in predicates begin at the context of the current step (i.e. that of the immediately preceding node test) and do not alter that context.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] All predicates must be satisfied for a match to occur.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] When the value of the predicate is numeric, it is syntactic-sugar for comparing against the node's position in the node-set (as given by the function `position()`).
[src:xpath-query/xpath] So `p[1]` is shorthand for `p[position()=1]` and selects the first `p` element child, while `p[last()]` is shorthand for `p[position()=last()]` and selects the last `p` child of the context node.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] In other cases, the value of the predicate is automatically converted to a Boolean.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] When the predicate evaluates to a node-set, the result is true when the node-set is non-empty.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Thus `p[@x]` selects those `p` elements that have an attribute named `x`.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] The reference to an attribute of the top-level element in the first predicate affects neither the context of other predicates nor that of the location step itself.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Predicate order is significant if predicates test the position of a node.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Each predicate takes a node-set returns a (potentially) smaller node-set.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] So `a[1][@href='help.php']` will find a match only if the first `a` child of the context node satisfies the condition `@href='help.php'`, while `a[@href='help.php'][1]` will find the first `a` child that satisfies this condition.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] XPath 1.0 defines four data types: node-sets (sets of nodes with no intrinsic order), strings, numbers and Booleans.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] Some of the more commonly useful functions are detailed below.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] returns a number representing the position of this node in the sequence of nodes currently being processed (for example, the nodes selected by an xsl:for-each instruction in XSLT).
[src:xpath-query/xpath] returns the number of nodes in the node-set supplied as its argument.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] converts any of the four XPath data types into a string according to built-in rules.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] If the value of the argument is a node-set, the function returns the string-value of the first node in document order, ignoring any further nodes.
[src:xpath-query/xpath] is removed and any sequences of whitespace characters are replaced by a single space.
